9":"1399","1 January 1439":"1 januari 1439","1493":"1493","1439":"1439","1406":"1406","Brightwell, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Brightwell, Berkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Wickers, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Markers Hall, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1399–1439":"1399–1439","1406–1439":"1406–1439","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1425":"1425","1399":"1399","1 January 1439":"1 January 1439","1493":"1493","1439":"1439","1406":"1406","Brightwell, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Brightwell, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","of Wickers, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Markers Hall, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vesey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Veazey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Veazey","meanings":["English (Rutland): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>enveisé</i> ‘playful’ (Old French <i>envoisié</i>), Latinized as <i>invesiatus</i> (compare medieval Latin <i>invasus</i> ‘possessed by a demon’) and paralleled by <i>lascivus</i> ‘wanton’. The first syllable was lost early, resulting in numerous dialectal and orthographic variants; only   Lenfestey   preserves the fuller form, with an intrusive medial <i>-t-</i>. There has also been some confusion with   Vessey  .","History: John Veazey came from England to MD in the late 17th century. Thomas Ward Veazey (born 1774) was a MD legislator and planter."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Vesey was born in 1399, in Essex, England, United Kingdom. He married Lady Jane Cardinall in 1425. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1439, in his hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1399–1439":"1399–1439","1406–1439":"1406–1439","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1425":"1425","1399":"1399","1 January 1439":"1. jaanuar 1439","1493":"1493","1439":"1439","1406":"1406","Brightwell, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Brightwell, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Wickers, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Markers Hall, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1399–1439":"1399–1439","1406–1439":"1406–1439","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1425":"1425","1399":"1399","1 January 1439":"1. tammikuuta 1439","1493":"1493","1439":"1439","1406":"1406","Brightwell, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Brightwell, Berkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Wickers, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Markers Hall, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1399–1439":"1399–1439","1406–1439":"1406–1439","1439–1493":"1439–1493","1425":"1425","1399":"1399","1 January 1439":"1 janvier 1439","1493":"1493","1439":"1439","1406":"1406","Brightwell, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Brightwell, Berkshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","of Wickers, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Markers Hall, Essex, England. United Kingdom":"Essex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Vesey est né en 1399, à Essex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Lady Jane Cardinall en 1425. Ils ont eu